16/06/2003
BANJA LUKA, Bosnia and Herzegovina (BiH) -- BiH Foreign Minister Mladen Ivanic said Sunday (15 June) that he believes the country will become an EU member between 2009 and 2012. 
At present, Ivanic estimates that BiH meets 5 to 10 per cent of the accession criteria. 
The country is drafting a feasibility study with answers to 400 questions filed by the EU with respect to the ongoing reforms. 
A mission of the European Commission has reviewed the first two sets of policy measures, while examinations of the third part of the criteria will continue over the next 15 days. 
The BiH Council of Ministers is targeting 2009 as the EU entry date, saying its goal is to speed up reforms.
In other news, High Representative Paddy Ashdown, BiH Council of Ministers Chairman Adnan Terzic, BiH Foreign Minister Mladen Ivanic, and BiH Central Bank Governor Peter Nicholl departed for Washington on Saturday. 
They will meet with officials of the World Bank and the International Financial Corporation on Monday, focusing on financing arrangements in connection with administrative reforms. 
The delegation will seek support from international financial institutions and from US authorities for promotion of business opportunities in BiH. 
(Dnevni Avaz, Dnevni List - 16/06/03; SRNA, BBC - 15/06/03)
